            <h1>Ethics of AI in Businesses</h1>
            <figure class="AI-ML">
                <img src="img/ethics.jpg" alt="Picture representing ethics in AI">
            </figure>

            <p class="what-is-AI">Organizations have always struggled with an important question: What defines ethics in
                business? This is significant as business ethics are key to building trust and fostering
                positive consumer relationships. Research shows that an increasing number of consumers prefer not to
                engage
                with companies they perceive as unethical. For instance, recent research sponsored by Google
                found that 86% of consumers choose to spend their money with businesses they believe uphold good values.
            </p>
            <p class="what-is-AI">Historical concerns in business ethics like honest accounting and health and safety
                continue to be pertinent, but the issue of ethical AI has also become increasingly prominent.
                Businesses are now challenged to address a new question: What constitutes ethical AI?</p>
            <p class="what-is-AI">In this context, AI ethics involves the development and application of AI technologies
                within a rigorous ethical framework that promotes values such as nondiscrimination, privacy,
                individual rights, and nonmanipulation.</p>
            <p class="what-is-AI">Companies committed to ethical AI practices go beyond just meeting legal standards.
                They
                adopt policies that surpass regulatory demands to ensure that the AI technologies they develop
                and deploy are harmless.</p>

            <figure class="AI-ML">
                <img src="img/ethics-2.jpg" alt="Picture of a ethics">
            </figure>
            <div>
                    <h3 class="what-is-AI">1. Algorithmic Bias</h3>
                    <p class="what-is-AI">Algorithms are fundamental to AI's capacity to enhance and streamline business processes.
                        However,
                        they also expose your organization to potential biases that could adversely affect both your
                        operations and your employees. Algorithmic bias refers to the systematic discrimination that may
                        arise when AI decision-making processes are swayed by biased data, leading to unjust results.
                    </p>
                    <p class="what-is-AI"><span class="ethics">Example:</span> consider how using AI to rapidly screen resumes could
                        expedite
                        identifying top candidates by meeting specific hiring criteria, thus refining the recruitment
                        process and freeing up time
                        for interviews and evaluations. However, if the AI is trained on biased data—like stereotypes
                        about
                        men in finance or women in nursing—it could unjustly favor certain candidates while disregarding
                        equally skilled applicants from varied backgrounds.</p>
                    <h3 class="what-is-AI">2. cybersecurity</h3>
                    <p class="what-is-AI">Cybersecurity represents a significant ethical challenge for companies utilizing AI technologies,
                        primarily due to their involvement with sensitive information. These systems, because of the
                        critical
                        data they process, become prime targets for cyberattacks, heightening the need for robust
                        security
                        measures to protect against potential breaches. This necessitates a proactive approach to
                        implementing
                        advanced security protocols to safeguard this data and maintain the integrity and
                        trustworthiness of
                        AI-driven operations.</p>
                    <h4><span class="ethics">Challenges in cybersecurity:</span></h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><span class="ethics">Phishing:</span> This refers to a deceptive practice where
                            cybercriminals
                            impersonate legitimate entities to trick individuals into disclosing sensitive personal or
                            financial information.</li>
                        <li><span class="ethics">Malware:</span> Derived from "malicious" and "software," this type of
                            program is designed to infiltrate and damage IT systems without permission, allowing
                            cybercriminals to steal data, disrupt operations, or gain unauthorized control.</li>
                        <li><span class="ethics">Ransomware:</span> A specific category of malware, ransomware locks
                            users
                            out of their data by encrypting files and then demands a ransom for decryption and data
                            restoration.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h3 class="what-is-AI">3. Privacy</h3>
                    <p class="what-is-AI">Ethical issues regarding AI and privacy center on the management of employee data, encompassing
                        its
                        collection, storage, and utilization. AI technologies have the capability to process extensive
                        quantities of both personal and professional information.
                        It is imperative that this data is securely safeguarded to prevent privacy breaches,
                        unauthorized
                        access, and improper use. Ensuring robust data protection measures are in place is crucial to
                        maintaining trust and adherence to privacy standards in the use of AI systems.</p>
                    <h3 class="what-is-AI">4. Inclusiveness</h3>
                    <p class="what-is-AI">Inclusion plays a critical role in business environments. It involves incorporating a variety of
                        groups into decision-making processes and valuing diverse perspectives and ideas within the
                        workplace. The goal of inclusion is to foster a balanced and harmonious
                        environment that respects and harnesses different viewpoints to enhance organizational
                        effectiveness
                        and innovation. This approach not only enriches the workplace culture but also drives better
                        business outcomes by engaging a broader range of talents and insights.</p>
            </div>
